-- LLM evaluation:

  yield findings ≡ "Tokyo's ramen landscape is organized by style and neighborhood. Key styles: (1) shoyu (soy sauce) — classic Tokyo style, clear broth, wavy noodles. (2) tonkotsu (pork bone) — rich, creamy, from Kyushu but hugely popular in Tokyo. (3) tsukemen — dipping noodles, thicker broth, pioneered at Taishoken. (4) miso — heartier, from Hokkaido tradition. (5) niboshi/iriko — dried sardine based, intensely savory.

Key ramen districts: Shinjuku (dense concentration, late-night options), Ebisu/Meguro (upscale, less tourist), Ikebukuro (especially for tsukemen), Tokyo Station area (Ramen Street in underground, curated selection).

Weekend considerations: Popular shops have 30-60 min waits, especially at lunch. Weekday-only shops exist but won't apply here. Some shops close early on Sundays. Ticket machine (券売機) ordering is standard — no Japanese needed, but know your order.

Notable shops: Fuunji (Shinjuku, tsukemen, expect 45-min wait), Afuri (Ebisu/multiple locations, yuzu shio, lighter style), Rokurinsha (Tokyo Station Ramen Street, tsukemen), Nakiryu (Otsuka, Michelin-starred tantanmen), Kagari (Ginza, chicken paitan), Ichiran (Shibuya/everywhere, tonkotsu, solo booths — tourist friendly but authentic)."

  yield recommendations ≡ [
    "Day 1 lunch: Fuunji in Shinjuku for tsukemen — arrive by 10:45 to beat the line. Near Shinjuku's architecture (Cocoon Tower, Mode Gakuen).",
    "Day 1 dinner: Afuri in Ebisu for yuzu shio ramen — lighter evening option. Ebisu has excellent walking architecture.",
    "Day 2 lunch: Kagari in Ginza for chicken paitan soba — rich but refined. Ginza has Nakagin Capsule Tower site and Ginza Six architecture.",
    "Day 2 dinner: Nakiryu near Otsuka for Michelin-starred tantanmen — worth the detour. 30-min train from central Tokyo.",
    "Backup: Rokurinsha at Tokyo Station Ramen Street if timing doesn't work — always accessible, excellent tsukemen."
  ]

