-- LLM evaluation:

  yield findings ≡ "Practical considerations for a Tokyo weekend:
- CASH: Japan is increasingly cashless but many ramen shops are cash-only (especially ticket machine ones). Carry ¥10,000-15,000 in cash. 7-Eleven ATMs accept foreign cards.
- TRANSIT: Suica/Pasmo IC card from airport. ¥1,500 deposit (¥500 refundable). Recharge at any station. Works on JR, Metro, buses, and many shops.
- LANGUAGE: Minimal Japanese needed. Train stations have English. Ramen shops use ticket machines (pictures help). Key phrases: sumimasen (excuse me), arigatou gozaimasu (thank you), kore kudasai (this please).
- TICKETS: Ramen ticket machines: insert money first, then press button for your order. Change is returned. Machines have photos.
- RESERVATIONS: Most ramen shops don't take reservations — just queue. Architecture sites mostly free/no-reservation. Some museums need online tickets (check 21_21 Design Sight).
- WEEKEND SPECIFICS: Harajuku/Omotesando busier on weekends. Shrines may have wedding ceremonies (bonus). Some business-district ramen shops closed on weekends (Ginza area mostly open).
- WEATHER: March — still cool (8-15°C). Layers. Comfortable walking shoes essential.
- ETIQUETTE: Slurping ramen is expected and polite. Remove shoes at shrines. Bow slightly when greeting."

  yield recommendations ≡ [
    "Get Suica card immediately at Narita/Haneda airport. Load ¥3,000 to start.",
