  - Total cells created dynamically: 9
  - Static cells (analyze-needs, synthesize, evaluate, etc.): 8
  - Total cells in final graph: 17

QUALITY TRAJECTORY:
  - Iteration 1: quality-score = 6 (solid core, 4 gaps)
  - Iteration 2: quality-score = 8 (all gaps filled, convergent)
  - ⊢∘ loop terminated after 2 iterations (threshold: 7)

BOOTSTRAP INSIGHT:
  The meta-cell (analyze-needs) made a key architectural decision: it split
  the problem into domain expertise (ramen, architecture), spatial reasoning
  (neighborhoods), temporal reasoning (itinerary), and pragmatics (tips).
  This decomposition was NOT predetermined — the meta-cell invented it by
  analyzing the task. The gap-filler wave then addressed what the first wave
  COULDN'T KNOW it was missing (breakfast, budget, rain, evening balance).

  This two-wave pattern — broad coverage then targeted depth — emerges
  naturally from the bootstrap loop. It mirrors how humans plan: rough
  outline first, then fill in gaps. But here the 'gaps' are identified
  by an oracle (evaluate-completeness) and filled by freshly spawned cells.

  The frontier grew monotonically: 0 → 5 → 9 domain cells. Each wave
  added information without removing any. The ⊢∘ loop drove convergence
  by repeatedly asking 'is this good enough?' and spawning new cells
  when the answer was no.
